<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUL 94 / Input price rises threaten profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT and DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Recent rises in raw material prices, combined with fierce price competition
in retail markets is threatening a profit squeeze in some manufacturing
sectors, official figures yesterday suggested.
A surge in the price of metals and other imported commodities pushed the
cost of raw materials and fuel for manufacturers up by a seasonally adjusted
0.8 per cent in June, the Central Statistical Office said.
However, output prices increases were broadly flat as intense competition
prevented UK companies from increasing the price of manufactured goods.
The cost of goods leaving factory gates, measured by the core output price
index, rose by only 0.1 per cent in June compared to May. Measured over the
year to June, the index rose by 1.9 per cent - its lowest annual growth
since November 1967. The core index excludes the volatile food, drink,
tobacco and fuel sectors,
The Treasury yesterday hailed the data as 'welcome good news' ahead of the
retail price index and average earnings data which will be published
tomorrow
But with the rise in input prices higher than City forecasts, the reaction
from analysts was mixed. Some fear that input price rises could fuel
inflation later this year. A recent Confederation of British Industry survey
indicated a sharp rise in manufacturers hoping to raise prices.
British companies now face a 'very different world', warned Mr Richard
Kersley, UK markets strategist at brokers BZW. Output costs rose faster than
input costs in the past two years, but the reversal of this pattern in
recent months meant companies now needed to focus on increasing sales
volumes, he said.
Commodities are calculated to be only 5 per cent of the total costs of UK
manufacturers and most companies were already operating with historically
strong levels of profit margins.
Mr David Owen, UK economist with brokers Kleinwort Benson, warned some
sectors heavily dependent upon commodities could suffer a profit squeeze.
Businessmen yesterday echoed this picture of growing pressure on margins. Mr
Rolf Rittner, raw materials purchasing director at BASF, the German
chemicals company, said: 'It has not been possible to close the gap between
increasing commodity prices and selling prices.' Mr Jean-Luc Schwitzguebel,
managing director of Swiss-owned Ciba Pigments in the UK, said price rises
among raw materials were forcing a search for alternatives.
Details, Page 12
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
