<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUL 94 / Housing funds sought in Germany
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Representatives of UK housing associations will today invite German mortgage
banks to raise finance for building inexpensive homes for rent or sale.
The Housing Corporation, the quango that distributes government grants to
English housing associations, is co-hosting a seminar in Frankfurt for more
than 30 German banks in its quest for new sources of funding for housing
associations.
Associations at present raise about 40 per cent of the cost of building new
homes from private-sector borrowing. They have raised Pounds 5.5bn since
1989, including more than Pounds 1bn through sterling debentures.
The corporation estimates that associations will need another Pounds 7bn
over the next four years, and is keen to expand the investor base. It hopes
to persuade the German banks to issue sterling Pfandbriefe, long-term
fixed-interest bonds, to raise funds.
Speakers at the seminar, organised in association with Rheinische
Hypothekenbank, include representatives of the Treasury and Department of
the Environment, as well as current UK lenders.
Foreign cash for bricks and mortar, Page 16
