<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUL 94 / Report on Archer probe 'this week'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN and KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A report on the investigation into Lord Archer's alleged involvement in
insider dealing is expected within a week, the Department of Trade and
Industry hinted strongly yesterday.
The DTI acknowledged the urgency to settle the affair as it came under
increasing pressure to provide a full explanation of the circumstances in
which it disclosed Lord Archer's name as part of the investigation.
Lord Archer publicly fended off questions about the inquiry for the second
day running yesterday when he hosted an auction to raise funds for the Globe
Theatre replica on London's South Bank.
However, Lord Archer's friends have been pressing for an early announcement
which they believe will clear his name.
Continuing uncertainty about the outcome of the investigation comes at a
time of increasing speculation about the ministerial reshuffle, expected
shortly.
Lord Archer was widely believed to be a candidate for a junior ministerial
post, such as sports minister, although his chances of achieving his
ambition of succeeding Sir Norman Fowler as Conservative party chairman were
not thought to be strong.
Mr Major, at the G7 summit in Naples yesterday, refused to say whether Lord
Archer would feature in the reshuffle if, as his friends claim, the former
party deputy chairman is exonerated by the DTI.
The prime minister said the matter must rest with the DTI and the
investigators appointed to look into allegations of insider trading. 'I
don't think it would be at all right for me to offer any further comment on
that whatsoever,' he said.
However, if the DTI gives Lord Archer a clean bill of health before the
reshuffle is announced, his chances of securing a government post are
belived to be the same as they would have been had details of the inquiry
remained confidential.
The investigation, launched in February, centres on share dealing in Anglia
TV during the run-up to an agreed takeover bid which sent shares soaring.
Lord Archer's wife, Mary, is a non-executive director of Anglia.
The DTI has refused to discuss details of the inquiry, but it is believed to
involve a single transaction involving 30,000 shares and a profit of about
Pounds 50,000.
</TEXT>
