<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUL 94 / Curb on food adverts urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Advertisements for fatty and sugary foods should be banned from children's
television, the National Food Alliance campaigning group says today in
submissions to the Independent Television Commission and the Advertising
Standards Authority.
The call comes as the group publishes the results of a poll conducted by
MORI which indicates that two-thirds of parents want to see tougher
restrictions on food advertising. Three-quarters of parents think that food
adverts do not encourage children to eat a healthy, balanced diet, said the
alliance.
The survey was carried out among 633 parents of children under the age of
15. Nearly half said their children persuaded them to buy advertised foods
or drinks which they would not otherwise have bought. The National Food
Alliance is an umbrella group of more than 50 organisations including the
British Dental Association, the National Farmers' Union and the Trades Union
Congress.
The submissions include proposals that:
Advertisements for fatty and sugary foods should be banned when large
numbers of children are likely to be viewing.
Advertising should provide more balanced nutrition messages.
The use of misleading or meaningless claims such as 'full of goodness' or
'wholesome' should be prohibited and health claims restricted unless
justified by sound medical evidence.
The Advertising Association, the body which represents both advertisers and
advertising professionals, said recently that children's diets may sometimes
be unsatisfactory. It added that some groups could be targeted in public
information programmes, but advertising could not solve these specific
problems.
</TEXT>
