<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUL 94 / Rules are 'too kind' to water groups
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Consumers have not had a fair deal on water prices since the industry was
privatised, the National Consumer Council says today, David Lascelles
writes.
The regulatory system has been too generous to the companies, says the
report, which comes two weeks before Mr Ian Byatt, industry regulator,
announces new price controls. Consumers have had to pay an unfair amount of
the industry's costs, it adds.
Operating profits of the 31 regulated companies rose by an annual average of
20 per cent from 1989-90 to 1992-93 and profit margins increased from 28.7
per cent to 35.6 per cent. Yet water bills for domestic customers have
increased by an average 67 per cent.
Although the water companies have faced huge costs to modernise
infrastructure, most of the cost has been passed on to consumers, and
companies have made little or no use of borrowings or rights issues.
</TEXT>
