<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUL 94 / Insurer paying Pounds 3,000 a recruit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Allied Dunbar, the insurance company, is paying its managers up to Pounds
3,000 for every new recruit who meets specific standards in an effort to
increase the quality of its sales force.
The scheme fits in with efforts in the life industry to take on more
experienced recruits who are deemed more likely to offer 'best advice' to
clients and so meet more exacting regulatory requirements.
In a scheme introduced this year believed to break new ground in the life
industry, Allied Dunbar is paying its biggest bonuses to managers who bring
into the company sales agents who have previous experience with life
products.
Smaller sums are paid for taking on people regarded as quality recruits by
dint of their age, background and previous salaries in other jobs.
Last year, in an experimental version of the scheme, about 45 of the
company's 350 managers qualified for recruitment bonuses, earning between
Pounds 3,000 and about Pounds 21,000.
While Allied Dunbar believes paying bonuses for recruits is an innovative
way to tackle some of the problems facing life insurance, some industry
critics believe that offering cash incentives to recruit sales people can
lead to managers bringing in large numbers of staff who may in some cases be
given inappropriate guidance.
Eight former sales agents and two present agents, all from Dunbar's office
in Chelmsford, Essex, have said they were given inflated promises from
company representatives about how much they could earn at Allied Dunbar and
then were given little management support to help them meet sales targets.
Allied Dunbar denies that any inflated promises were made, although it
added: 'We acknowledge that there was poor management support at Chelmsford,
and we have taken steps to change the management.'
</TEXT>
