<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUL 94 / Public pay 'runs ahead of guideline'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government's 'clumsy' intervention in the Railtrack negotiations has
highlighted the fact that it is unsure whether its public-sector pay policy
is working, according to the independent pay analysts Incomes Data Services.
An IDS analysis of the public sector freeze on pay bills finds that most
groups have settled for between 2.5 and 3 per cent, comfortably above last
year's 1.5 per cent norm.
'The pattern of awards suggests that many public-sector employers have used
the inflation rate and the Pay Review Body awards as yardsticks for pay
increases and then aimed for efficiency savings to match,' says IDS.
In local government the 2.9 per cent Pay Review Body award to teachers has
been a strong factor in pay decisions. In the NHS, the administrative and
clerical staff have been offered 1.95 per cent. Other groups have been made
opening offers of 1.75 per cent, which unions have rejected.
IDS says private sector deals are starting to push up over 3 per cent. The
increases include performance-based rises of between 0 and 9 per cent for
38,000 retail staff at Boots the Chemist (adding 3 per cent to pay scales)
and a flat rate increase of Pounds 6 a week from July for 52,000 staff at
Marks and Spencer, worth an average 4 per cent to a sales assistant.
IDS Report 668. For further information contact Alistair Hatchett on 071 250
3434.
