<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUL 94 / Junior ministerial aides suspended pending inquiry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two junior ministerial aides were last night suspended from their
departmental duties following newspaper allegations that they had been
willing to accept money for tabling parliamentary questions.
Downing Street said Mr Richard Ryder, the chief whip, planned to tell Mr
David Tredinnick and Mr Graham Riddick that they were suspended as
parliamentary private secretaries - the lowest rung on the ministerial
ladder - pending the outcome of 'any inquiry which may be instituted by the
committee of privileges'.
If there was no inquiry by the privileges committee, the two would be
suspended while 'an internal inquiry' was conducted, Downing Street said.
Mr Tredinnick, the MP for Bosworth, is parliamentary private secretary to
Sir Wyn Roberts, a Welsh Office minister. Mr Riddick, MP for Colne Valley,
fulfils the same role for Mr John MacGregor, the transport secretary.
The speed of Downing Street's reaction was interpreted as a sign of the
government's continuing sensitivity to any suggestion of impropriety in the
wake of a series of embarrassments this year.
Yesterday's move followed newspaper allegations that the pair had been
willing to table official questions in the House of Commons in return for
Pounds 1,000.
The two men, who both deny wrongdoing, were among 10 Conservative and 10
Labour MPs selected at random and approached by a Sunday Times reporter
posing as a businessman.
Mr Riddick - who the newspaper said had returned his Pounds 1,000 payment -
said yesterday he decided it would be 'inappropriate' to accept the fee
because the amount of work was very small. He said he was taking advice
'with a view to consideration of legal action'.
Mr Tredinnick said he refused to accept payment 'and in any case if I had
agreed to do so, providing I had registered that interest, I would not have
been in any way contravening regulations'.
He said he resented 'very much' that the newspaper had 'gone out of its way
to try and set up members of parliament'. Mr Dale Campbell-Savours, the
Labour MP for Workington, said he was planning to ask Miss Betty Boothroyd,
the Speaker, to investigate the allegations, which left him 'aghast'.
</TEXT>
