<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUL 94 / Exaggerated death of the county council
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The survival of county councils now looks increasingly likely in much of
England as the review of the structure of English local government
approaches the end of its first stage.
By the end of this week the Local Government Commission for England, chaired
by Sir John Banham, will have published its recommendations for all but
three counties.
Of the 20 on which proposals have been published since the beginning of
June, only four rule out retaining county councils. In the others the
existing two-tier structure of county and district councils remains an
option.
The commission must now submit its proposals for local consultation. The
options will be included in leaflets to be sent to every household in the
counties affected.
If local opinion comes out in favour of preserving counties and districts,
this would offer the government the opportunity to back away from its policy
of creating new unitary councils, combining the functions of counties and
districts.
With growing opposition to change from Conservative backbenchers, ministers
could say that the review had delivered a verdict that only minimal change
was necessary.
The legislation setting up the review requires the commissioners to state a
preferred option when they draw up their reports.
However, the commissioners have presented their latest recommendations as
the start of a consultation, emphasising that they would be happy with any
of the alternatives they present.
They insist that the exercise is not a referendum, as other factors such as
cost and viability must be taken into account. But a strong vote against
wholesale reform would make it hard for the commission to recommend change.
Commissioners' statements also reflect lack of enthusiasm for change. Sir
John told an audience in Leicestershire that 'the level of popular support
for unitary districts in England is very low indeed' and that the commission
was 'not in the business of changing for its own sake'.
The commission is also emphasising the potential costs of reorganisation in
its literature. It said annual savings could be as little as Pounds 1m from
the proposed new unitary structures in Lancashire and Surrey, while the
set-up costs could be as high as Pounds 28m and Pounds 44m respectively.
However, some changes seem certain to emerge from the process. These
include:
Unitary status for older cities such as Leicester, Nottingham, Portsmouth
and Southampton, and fast-growing newer cities such as Milton Keynes and
Swindon.
The return, with unitary structures, of some small counties, such as
Herefordshire, Huntingdonshire and Rutland.
Unitary structures for small counties which are easily split, such as
Bedfordshire.
Extension of unitary structure for towns bordering large metropolitan areas
 -such as Slough and Dartford on the edge of London and Warrington near
Greater Manchester.
But the two-tier system now seems set to survive outside major cities,
particularly in large counties which have economies of scale, such as Essex,
Kent, Hampshire, Leicestershire and Nottinghamshire.
Proposals for nine counties will be announced this week: Devon and Essex
today (although proposals for Essex were leaked last week); Durham, and East
and West Sussex tomorrow; Northumberland and Northamptonshire on Wednesday;
and Norfolk and Suffolk on Thursday.
Proposals for the three remaining counties - Cornwall, Hertfordshire and
Shropshire - will be published in September.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
