<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUL 94 / World Cup '94: Sweden win as Romania pay heavy penalty
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Swedish goalkeeper Thomas Ravelli clinched a place for his team in the World
Cup semi-finals for the first time in 36 years by saving two penalties in
the sudden-death shoot-out after a see-saw game that left the sides tied 2-2
after extra time.
Brolin gave Sweden the lead after a well-worked free-kick in the 79th
minute, but Raducioiu kept Romania in the tournament with an 89th minute
equaliser against the run of play, then scored a second goal during the
first period of extra time.
Kennet Andersson put the Swedes back on terms by making the score 2-2 in the
115th minute.
The penalty shoot-out moved into sudden death after five kicks for each side
failed to break the tie.
Each team missed one shot to leave them level at 4-4.
Dumitrescu for Romania and Larsson for Sweden scored the next two before
Ravelli turned his 115th national team appearance - which tied a Swedish
record - into a triumph.
He dived for a one-handed save on a hesitant kick by Romanian defender
Belodedici to set up a clash with Brazil - a rematch of a first-round game
that ended 1-1.
As the Swedish players leapt for joy at the end of the shoot-out, Romania's
players sat motionless in the centre circle, reliving the heartbreak of four
years ago when they were knocked out of the World Cup on penalties by
Ireland in Genoa.
</TEXT>
