<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUL 94 / Israeli settlers yield to army
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Leaders of militant Jewish settlers yesterday agreed to a compromise aimed
at averting a showdown with Israeli soldiers over protesters occupying flats
in the West Bank. Their conciliatory move came soon after the government
sent in hundreds of troops ready to evict the protesters with force.
The Israeli government meanwhile ordered the Gaza Strip - now under
Palestinian administration - to be sealed off from early today. The order,
depriving thousands of Palestinian labourers entry into Israel for at least
24 hours, follows clashes between Israeli troops and Palestinians at a
border checkpoint.
Both moves came as Mr Yassir Arafat, PLO chairman, made further preparations
for his permanent homecoming. He is due to attend a formal farewell ceremony
in Tunis today.
Faced with an imminent clash with troops, radical leaders of Jewish settlers
promised to try to persuade protesters to move out today from the
government-built flats they have been occupying since Friday near the Kiryat
Arba Jewish settlement.
But they said it would take all their powers of persuasion to influence the
protesters, demonstrating against Israel's peace moves and the killing of a
Jewish girl by an Arab gunman. The settlers, including women and children,
have taken over vacant flats in a street peopled by Palestinians.
The despatch of soldiers to the settlement raised the prospect of the first
armed showdown with extremist Jewish settlers. If the troops force
evictions, this would signal to Jewish settlers and the PLO that the
government is prepared to take on settlers in a struggle which both sides
say is a potential 'time-bomb' in the peace process.
Mr David Libai, justice minister, said after a cabinet meeting yesterday
that the 15 families who had occupied the buildings would have to leave or
be forcibly removed. Mr Shimon Peres, Israeli foreign minister, said the
settlers were a danger to democracy.
Kiryat Arba settler leaders at first warned that any use of force could end
in bloodshed. Later they agreed to talks with President Ezer Weizman to try
to avert a clash.
The Israelis said Gaza was being sealed off so that the army could
re-organise procedures for Palestinians to cross into Israel at the Erez
checkpoint. They said two Israeli officers and a soldier were injured when
several thousand Palestinians trying to enter Israel stormed the checkpoint.
</TEXT>
