<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUL 94 / Ukrainian rivals dispute lead as early results indicate
close race
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRYSTIA FREELAND and JILL BARSHAY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KIEV, AND AGENCIES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Early results from yesterday's Ukrainian presidential election indicated a
close race, with both candidates claiming to be in the lead.
The incumbent, President Leonid Kravchuk, was polling strongly in
nationalist western regions, while Mr Leonid Kuchma, a former prime
minister, was well ahead in the Russian-speaking east.
An adviser to Mr Kravchuk claimed early today that the president had won
with a five-point margin over his adversary. But Mr Kuchma's campaign team
claimed partial returns suggested their candidate held an eight-point lead.
The outcome was not expected to be clear until late today.
Just over 69 per cent of registered voters went to the polls in the run-off
election between the two men - about the same as in the first round of
voting last month and far in excess of the 50 per cent turnout needed for
the election to be valid.
Voting was particularly heavy in the fiercely nationalist western Ukraine,
while turnout was lower in the Russian-leaning eastern regions.
As in neighbouring Belarus, where presidential run-offs were also held
yesterday, Ukraine's presidential debate centred on national independence
and links with Russia, which still exerts a powerful influence over all the
former Soviet republics.
Mr Kravchuk has sought to shift the campaign away from his disastrous
economic record and positioned himself as the sole guarantor of
independence, while portraying Mr Kuchma as Russia's henchman because of his
wish for closer ties with Moscow.
Fighting for his job on nationalist issues could win Mr Kravchuk a second
mandate, a remarkable achievement for a leader whose reign has been marked
by deep industrial decline and hyperinflation.
But his strategy has opened a Pandora's box of potential national discord
between western and central Ukraine, which tend to back the president, and
Russian-speaking eastern Ukraine, where Mr Kuchma's pro-Russian agenda is
highly popular.
Early results indicated that Mr Kravchuk was getting more than 90 per cent
of votes in the Lvov and Ternopil districts, strong nationalist areas.
In the east, Mr Kuchma was credited with more than 70 per cent in Kharkov
and 80 per cent in the conservative Donbass coalfield. He had 82 per cent in
the pro-Russian Crimean peninsula.
In contrast with the presidential race, which has offered Ukrainians an
often agonising choice between 'two evils', many of the mayoral and
gubernatorial elections also held yesterday throughout the country promised
real change. For example, Kiev's mayoral contest is pitting a democratic
market reformer against a presidential appointee, albeit a progressive one.
</TEXT>
