<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 94 / Food &amp; Drink: Affordable claret
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Traditional British wine merchants - notably Adnams of Southwold, Suffolk,
Corney &amp; Barrow of London EC1, Harveys of Bristol, Lay &amp; Wheeler of
Colchester, Essex, Peatlings, of Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk and The Wine
Society of Stevenage, Hertfordshire - tend to offer more exciting petits
chateaux red bordeaux than the supermarkets because of their long
relationships with Bordeaux merchants.
Waitrose, however, has the richly plummy Chateau Les Tonnelles de Fronsac
1990, at Pounds 4.99, and the creditable second wine of a fifth growth Medoc
in Baron Villeneuve du Ch Cantemerle 1990 at Pounds 7.95. (In very general
terms, such 'second wines' are generally worth buying only in good vintages
such as 1990s.)
Oddbins has a particularly good selection of red bordeaux under Pounds 10 a
bottle with a list full of plums, while Thresher/Bottoms Up/Wine Rack wine
shops are good on the Lurton family's well-made wines.
Another family whose name spells wine quality is Thienpont. Their juicy but
structured Cotes de Francs wines are still good value and are available from
Tanners of Shrewsbury, Shropshire, and Seckford Wines of Ipswich, Suffolk.
Specific goodies from Oddbins include Ch Tour de Mirambeau, Pounds 5.29 and
the blended Michel Lynch 1990, Pounds 5.99, a Mouton Cadet trying harder if
ever there was one; and the daringly opulent Ch Lilian-Ladouys 1990 at
Pounds 9.99.
Majestic wine warehouses have long stocked Ch de Sours (the 1990 is Pounds
5.79) and Ch Meaume (the 1990 is Pounds 4.99), both made energetically by
Englishmen keenly aware of the demands of the wine world outside Bordeaux.
Thresher/Wine Rack/Bottoms Up's best buy is probably the peppery Ch Guibon
1992 at Pounds 4.69, and oak fans will enjoy Peter Sichel's Sirius 1990 at
Pounds 5.99.
Two wines made by the owner of the celebrated Ch Le Tertre Roteboeuf, with
ambition and technique that completely ignore their humble appellations, are
Ch Roc de Cambes, Pounds 8.73 from Corney &amp; Barrow, and the cheaper Domaine
de Cambes, Pounds 66 per case ex-cellars from Mark Savage, Guiting Power,
Cheltenham (0451-850896).
Other names worth looking out for include Chx Cote-Montpezat, Fontenille, Le
Grand Verdus, de Haux, Jonqueyres, du Juge, Lassime, Monbadon, Parenchere,
Suau and Turcaud, as well as Domaine de Courteillac.
An error in transmission meant that we gave the wrong price for New Zealand
wines mentioned last week. Top bottlings of the Sauvignon Blancs, including
Cloudy Bay, Hunters, Jackson Estate, Vavasour and Wairau River, are all
under Pounds 10 a bottle.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
