<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 94 / Finance and the Family: Independent child of a powerful
parent - The Professionals / Seeing how the professionals look after their
clients' money gives an insight into managing your own better. That's the
theory behind Joanna Slaughter's series on private client investment
managers. Today: BZW Portfolio Management Ltd
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOANNA SLAUGHTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BZW Portfolio Management Ltd (PML) is the investment and financial
management division of the BZW Group, the international investment banking
arm of the Barclays Group, and the advantages of this parentage are
considerable.
Take analysts: BZW has more than 200, who are a major source of research for
PML's portfolio managers, while Barclays provides an extensive distribution
network to assist the search for new clients. Well over half PML's private
clients are introduced through the bank's high street branches, or through
the Barclays Group as a whole.
The obverse of this particular coin is that PML must work hard to reassure
its private clients that there are no conflicts of interest, and that it is
not the poodle of either the Barclays Group or BZW.
PML was established as a separate legal entity; it has its own board of
directors, which is separate to those of the BZW trading companies; and it
distances itself physically by occupying a separate building. Peter
Saunders, head of portfolio management, says: 'We are independent - we do
what is best for the client.
'For instance, we wouldn't necessarily take a view that agreed with BZW
Securities because a great deal of the output from securities houses is
aimed at institutional investors and we have to interpret research for the
private individual.'
PML also thinks hard before using any group product for private clients.
Saunders explains: 'If we go into a Barclays unit trust, we have to be able
to prove that it is positively better than any other.'
The directors describe PML's investment style as 'conservative but
pro-active, aided by our direct line access to research and sophisticated
technology'. This technology includes a pilot scheme with a system devised
by James Bevan, a PML director.
With this, market forecasts are fed into a computer programme that has the
history of markets and currencies already in it. The system then produces a
suggested asset allocation. 'It is a tool, not a full answer,' says
Saunders. 'It rationalises history into a reasoned view of the world, and it
takes into account more circumstances than you could keep in your head.'
Saunders adds: 'We have a house view on pretty much everything on the world
markets and on the right allocation for general categories of clients.'
Portfolio managers are asked to interpret the house view in relation to
their clients.
Insight into the firm's thinking can be found in the latest asset allocation
guidelines for private clients who are looking either for 'wealth growth' or
for 'wealth preservation'.
For clients wanting income from a wealth growth portfolio, the guideline
allocations are UK cash, 10.53 per cent; conventional gilts, 25 per cent;
convertibles, 21.60 per cent; UK equities, 40 per cent; and emerging
markets, 2.86 per cent.
For clients who are seeking capital appreciation, the suggested split is UK
cash, 12.61 per cent; conventional gilts, 10 per cent; index-linked gilts,
7.5 per cent; UK equities 46.14 per cent; North America, 2.5 per cent;
Continental Europe, 10 per cent; Pacific Rim and Japan, 3.75 per cent; and
emerging markets, 7.5 per cent.
On wealth preservation portfolios, more emphasis is placed on gilts for
income and UK equities for growth. The suggested income divide is UK cash,
12.50 per cent; conventional gilts, 30 per cent; index-linked gilts, 1.65
per cent; convertibles, 16.67 per cent; UK equities, 32.93 per cent; and
overseas equities, 6.25 per cent.
The growth guideline allocations are UK cash, 11.91 per cent; conventional
gilts, 10 per cent; index-linked gilts, 10 per cent; UK equities, 52.50 per
cent; North America, 4.34 per cent; continental Europe, 2.50 per cent;
Pacific rim and Japan, 3.75 per cent; and emerging markets, 5 per cent.
PML prides itself on providing bespoke investment management within
parameters set by the private clients themselves. The 20 portfolio managers
who deal with private client money meet each morning at 8.15 to discuss
global economic or political developments, overnight market movements and
specific stocks.
Traditionally, PML held a buy/hold/sell stock list, but this has been
developed recently to include the measurement of technical factors. The
stock selection list is reviewed constantly and the performance of its
shares is used to demonstrate the firm's investment track record.
Charles Pinney, the director in charge of offshore portfolio services, says:
'There is no edict saying these are the stocks managers must hold for
clients, but they are a recommendation to a manager if he is buying now. If
he gets very enthusiastic about a stock, he can get it put on the list.'
Currency hedges are used to a limited extent, and 'individually tailored'
derivatives' programmes are available through BZW. The firm also has access
to group expertise if clients want management of other assets, such as
property.
Portfolio performances are monitored rigorously, and PML is reviewing its
information technology to assist the process. 'Anyone can have a streak of
bad luck,' Saunders points out, 'and we encourage managers to come and tell
us if anything is going wrong.'
Average turnover within the portfolios is 30 per cent, and Saunders says:
'Whenever we make changes in a portfolio, we write to the client. It has
become part of the service, although some of our competitors have given up
doing this.'
PML also differs from some competitors in its willingness to take clients on
an advisory, as well as a discretionary, basis. Saunders describes
investment houses that will not offer an advisory service as 'arrogant'. He
argues: 'It is not client-sensitive. What is important is that you give
advisory clients just as much attention as your discretionary clients,
rather than making them tail-end Charlies.'
PML manages Pounds 1.3bn on behalf of private clients, and the average
portfolio of new clients is Pounds 750,000. But the directors will not say
how many private clients there are. Perhaps some professional secrecy is
required from even the most independent arm of a large banking group.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Investment managers: factfile 3
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
BZW
(BZW Portfolio Management Ltd)
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Established: 1986 (origins in 18th century)
Regulator: SFA
Number of offices in UK: One (London)
Number of offices worldwide: In most major financial centres as part of
the Barclays Group
Funds under management: Pounds 1.3bn (private clients) Pounds 50 bn
(BZW Group)
Number of UK private clients: Not disclosed
Number of expatriate/foreign national private clients: Not disclosed
Minimum investment for private clients: Pounds 250,000
Current asset allocation for private clients: 68% equities, 20% bonds,
12% cash
Average annual portfolio turnover: 30%
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Fees: Discretionary, minimum fee Pounds 1,500 pa (0.75% on first Pounds
1m, 0.6% on next Pounds 2m, 0.5% on next Pounds 2m, thereafter
negotiable); Advisory, minimum fee Pounds 2,000 pa (1% on first Pounds
1m, 0.7% on next Pounds 2m, 0.6% on next Pounds 2m, thereafter
negotiable).
