<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 94 / Markets: Bank shares - 'don't panic' - The Bottom Line
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Abbey National and Midland Bank have fired some warning shots at their
competitors in retail banking over the last couple of weeks, and shares in
UK banks have been looking slightly wounded.
Despite the advancing gunfire, however, the message for investors seems to
be 'don't panic'. It is hard to find an analyst who does not think the
market has been 'oversensitive'.
Bank shares first fell sharply at the end of last month after Abbey, the
former building society turned bank, said that it was reducing the annual
percentage rate (APR) on overdrafts from 18.4 per cent to 9.9 per cent.
Another front was opened by Midland last Tuesday, when it launched a
campaign aimed explicitly at overcoming the inertia in the personal
financial market and attracting customers from other banks.
And on Wednesday, the government announced that building societies would be
given new powers to enable them to compete more effectively.
Fears that these are the first signs that banks will use - or will have to
use - the capital they have started to accumulate to compete for business on
price have caused the bank sector to underperform the FT All-share price
index by more than 2 per cent since late June.
Shares in National Westminster Bank fell from 456p on 29 June to 435p on
Thursday. Over the same time, TSB shares fell 12p to 198p, Barclays shares
fell 6p to 529p, and Lloyds Bank shares lost 1p to 538p.
Even the aggressors have not remained unscathed: HSBC Holdings, which owns
Midland, fell from 702p to 692p while Abbey dropped from 406p to 393p.
But fears of an all-out price war seem exaggerated, as the moves by Abbey
and Midland may in practice amount to no more than marketing skirmishes.
Abbey has made little secret that the cut in overdraft rate is directed
towards increasing its 1.4m of the estimated 33m personal current accounts,
and some analysts doubt that the 10 per cent overdraft will remain a lasting
feature of retail banking once some advance has been made.
The Midland initiative of a pledge of Pounds 10 for every error it makes in
the course of setting up a new account is perhaps even an encouraging sign
for the banks in terms of the direction competition may take. As Peter
Toeman, banking analyst at Hoare Govett, put it: 'Competition on service
quality is much more lenient than competition on price'.
He points out that the barriers to moving current accounts remain quite
high, and that the number of those who change accounts in any one year could
double to 1m and still represent only 3 per cent of the customer base.
Competition on price is unlikely to be structural and more likely to take
the form of temporary, special offers - perhaps on personal loan rates or
credit cards.
Even if banks did feel obliged to cut margins on core services to personal
customers, they are aware of ways of cushioning the blow.
During 1989, for example, when Abbey National and Nationwide building
society forced the sector towards giving interest on current accounts, the
banks responded by introducing a new product into which existing customers
could transfer.
This not only spread the cost over time but meant they also obtained more
information about their customers.
Despite Midland, the continuing reluctance of personal customers to change
banks makes competition weak, leading analysts to believe that banks will be
able to avoid substantial cuts in their wide margins on most retail
business.
Instead, they believe that retail margins can afford to fall slightly
without damaging the banks' business, because they will be reflecting
realistically the lower costs of lending in a less risky environment.
As Hugh Pye, banking analyst at BZW, put it: 'Margins are incredibly fat,
and likely to remain so.' Good news for those who invest in banks - less
good news for them in their capacity as customers.
</TEXT>
