<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 94 / The Long View: Some bitter home truths
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An engine of the British economy has lost power. The housing market, which
gave such a spectacular push to the economic boom of the late 1980s, has
failed to gather momentum during the past year's economic recovery. The
Nationwide and Halifax building societies, which publish the two leading
house price indices, are at odds over whether house prices rose or fell
slightly in June, but they are united in calculating that the rise over the
past 12 months has been only 1 per cent.
Forecasts are being trimmed. Halifax has cut its 5 per cent estimate of 1994
house price inflation to 2 or 3 per cent and John Wriglesworth, of the City
investment bank UBS, has halved his 7 per cent forecast. My own
cautiously-wide forecast of 0 to 5 per cent, which I made here in October,
is still on track but I am surprised at the weakness of prices in the past
few months.
Opinions in the London area have been influenced by the mini-boom which has
been proceeding in some areas in reflection of soaring incomes in the City.
Up-market property in the more desirable areas of London and the south-east
has been shifting quite fast, and at rising prices. But, plainly, that is
not true of the country as a whole.
Generally, personal incomes have been far from buoyant and the tax increases
effective in April have, obviously, made people more reluctant to take on
big new commitments. That was evident, too, in the relative weakness of
consumer credit in May.
Moreover, mortgage interest rates have gone up sharply since February - at
any rate, if you look at the fixed-rate loans which have become popular.
Mortgages fixed for five years now cost about 9 rather than 7 per cent
(measured by the annual percentage rate); and although variable rate loans
are available at about 8 per cent, no less a figure than Bank of England
governor Eddie George has given notice that such rates linked to short-term
money market rates may go up quite soon.
Long-term measures of the fundamental value in housing are now giving
reasonably positive messages. The ratio of average price to average income
is under 3.5, and close to a 'normal' level. The TSB first-time buyer
'affordability' index is significantly more favourable than it has been
since the early 1980s. But the average first-time buyer must take on a 90
per cent mortgage of Pounds 41,000. And a great many home-owners have been
through a terrible experience since 1989.
A recent survey, financed by the Joseph Rowntree Foundation, found that a
third of householders in Luton knew someone whose home had been repossessed.
The statistics of housing market agony, such as those of repossessions and
negative equity, are moderating but the failure of the forecasts of rising
prices to come true will come as a bitter disappointment to those still
trapped in over-mortgaged homes.
Although negative equity has been declining since its estimated peak of
Pounds 12bn in the first quarter of 1993, it was still Pounds 7.6bn at the
beginning of this year, according to the Bank of England. Some 70 per cent
of that was concentrated in London and the south-east.
Mortgage lenders expressed disappointment this week with the Pounds 1.5bn
level of net new lending in May, less than in April and little higher than
May last year. But outstanding mortgage debt is now Pounds 365bn, about 50
per cent higher than at the peak of the boom in mid-1989. Mortgages account
for most of the UK's comparatively high level of personal sector
indebtedness (debt is 80 per cent of income, twice as high as in Germany).
There is a limit to the burden that ordinary people will take on. They now
know that inflation will not bail them out: those who borrowed themselves
into a financial trap in 1988 or 1989 are mostly still stuck there. Real
interest rates are high, and the tax relief on interest payments is now
fairly trivial: the cost to the government of Miras peaked at around Pounds
8bn in 1990-91 and is expected to be down to just Pounds 2.5bn next fiscal
year.
The exposure to this debt burden is highly skewed: it is borne mostly by
young people, especially in the south of the country. Only 50 per cent of
northern home-owners have a mortgage, compared with 60 per cent in the
south.
In the past, southerners have been ready to borrow more - both absolutely
and as a proportion of the house price - than their northern counterparts.
This was the price of taking part in the booming southern economy; and,
anyway, the more you borrowed, the more profit you would make - wouldn't
you?
Some of the forecasts of house price recovery have been based on the
supposition that the southern differentials would be, at least partly,
restored. But suppose, instead, that southerners act like cautious
northerners in future?
Moreover, the Rowntree Foundation report (called The Challenges for Housing
Policy) argues convincingly that home ownership has been a disaster for too
many young people and families, and that first-time buyers continue to be
lured into the market with loan-to-value ratios still as high as at any time
since 1982. More housing for rent, and the deferment of house purchase until
later in life, as in Germany, might reduce the risks to individuals of
future housing market booms and busts.
Booms and busts are, of course, what chancellor Kenneth Clarke is aiming to
avoid. But the loss of momentum in the housing recovery is one of the early
effects of the rise in long-term interest rates, and it poses a threat to
the pace of the economic upswing in general. Clarke might also wonder how
the Tories will be able to win the next general election without a feel-good
contribution from some degree of house price buoyancy within a year or two.
One of the more curious statistics in the Rowntree survey is that most
homeowners, when questioned in 1993, thought their houses were worth more
than in 1989. But buyers, it seems, have a very different view. That is why
the price recovery is scarcely happening.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P655  Subdividers and Developers.
    P9531 Housing Programs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
    ECON  Economic Indicators.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
