<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 94 / World Stock Markets (Asia Pacific): Nikkei down amid
regional uncertainty
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Technical trading dominated the day's activity, with most investors absent
ahead of the G7 meeting in Naples. The Nikkei index declined on
arbitrage-linked selling, writes Emiko Terazono in Tokyo.
The 225 average lost 93.51 to 20,526.51, marginally lower on the week. It
saw a high of 20,691.84 in the morning on buying by individual investors,
but institutional and foreign investors remained inactive and the index
touched a low of 20,440.09 in the last hour of trading.
Volume totalled 342m shares against 283m. Traders said the bulk of the
business was linked to the settlement of July index options contracts.
Investors also remained sidelined ahead of the US employment figures, which
are expected to give some indication of short-term US monetary policy.
The Topix index of all first section stocks fell 7.55 to 1,660.88 while the
Nikkei 300 lost 1.37 to 301.48. Losers outnumbered gainers by 640 to 318
with 206 unchanged and, in London, the ISE/Nikkei 50 index rose 1.21 to
1,347.54.
Terumo, the disposable medical equipment supply manufacturer, which saw its
share price rise earlier in the week on its development of a three
dimensional television, fell Y50 to Y1,120 on profit taking.
Nippon Telegraph and Telephone fell Y6,000 to Y855,000 on reports that the
company's office was being searched by police in connection with the arrest
of an employee in an alleged bribery case.
In Osaka, the OSE average fell 97.53 to 23,112.00 in volume of 30.3m shares.
Roundup
The course of US interest rates, yesterday's US jobs data and the start of
the G7 summit left several markets apprehensive.
HONG KONG's Hang Seng index closed 57.90 down on the day, and another 2.3
per cent lower on the week. Turnover shrank from HKDollars 3.37bn to a
preliminary HKDollars 2.48bn. Luoyang Glass H shares made their debut at
HKDollars 3.31 and tumbled to HKDollars 2.92 at the close, against their
public offer price of HKDollars 3.65.
BANGKOK fell after the Thai opposition filed no-confidence motions against
four government ministers and the deputy prime minister, Amnuay Viravan
resigned his posts in the coalition government and his own party. The SET
index fell 15.52 to 1,287.34, up 1.1 per cent on the week, in moderate
turnover of Bt5.07bn.
MANILA took profits and the composite index dropped 45.38 to 2,583.85, 4.1
per cent lower on the week with the telephone stock, PLDT down 3.8 per cent
to its year's low of 1,480 pesos.
WELLINGTON hit a new 1994 low with the NZSE-40 index down 10.33 at 1,955.93,
off 1.4 per cent with brokers fairly phlegmatic about the marking down
process.
TAIPEI put on 1.6 per cent in heavy trade, led by financials, electronics
and some fund shares. The weighted index rose 96.45 to 6,191.79, or 4.4 per
cent higher on the week.
SYDNEY rallied in late trade to finish marginally stronger, helped by a
round of afternoon bargain-hunting. The All Ordinaries index finished 2.7
higher at 1,964.9, off its intraday low of 1,957.0, and unchanged on the
week.
KUALA LUMPUR rebounded from early doldrums to close higher in retail-led
buying, sparked by expectations of a technical rebound following
one-and-a-half weeks of sluggish trade and growing expectations of
elections.
The composite index ended 6.41 higher at 987.78, but still 1.6 per cent
lower over the week.
SINGAPORE overcame recent weakness as bargain hunting developed at the lower
levels and the Straits Times Industrials index ended 16.93 higher at
2,162.94, still 2.2 per cent lower on the week.
SEOUL saw a technical rebound following recent retreats and the composite
stock index added 3.25 to 948.96 for a 1.4 per cent rise on the week.
Financials lost momentum after the government decided to delay a plan to
foster financial conglomerates.
JAKARTA was mixed in moderate trading although activity picked up on news
that the government planned to raise its 49 per cent limit on foreign share
ownership. The official index ended 1.90 lower to close at 452.20, for a 1.3
per cent rise on the week.
