<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 94 / London Stock Exchange: Kingfisher busy
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Stores group Kingfisher jumped 12 to 528p as the company's joint broker, the
notoriously secretive Cazenove, turned more positive on the stock.
Cazenove never comments on its moves but sources close to Kingfisher said
the brokerage house had taken the view that the derating of the company by
the City had been overdone. Cazenove is thought to have reasoned that the
owner of chains Woolworths, B&amp;Q, Comet and Superdrug was taking a more
pragmatic attitude to pricing. The move follows a more positive view taken
by BZW last week.
Body Shop fell 2 1/2 to 243p after announcing that Mrs Anita Roddick and Mr
Gordon Roddick had sold 3.5m shares at 240p each reducing their stake to
25.4 per cent. The sale raised Pounds 8.4m which is targeted at charity and
company projects.
Leading pharmaceuticals stocks were supported by some institutional buying
but are likely to open weaker on Monday as a result of the late plunge in
the dollar. Glaxo ended 10 better at 571p, Wellcome, which filed for
approval of a new anti-herpes treatment, added 5 at 606p and Zeneca gained 2
to 737p.
International news and electronic information group Reuters Holdings is also
likely to suffer but its shares received a boost from a Kleinwort Benson buy
recommendation ahead of interim figures at the end of the month. Reuters
gained 3 to 464p
Printing and packing group Bowater slumped 13 to 430 after the group
announced that it had lost its executive director, Mr Stuart Wallis to
Fisons, which gained 2 on the news but closed unchanged at 138.
British Gas attracted keen interest with the shares moving up to 277p before
slipping back late in the session and closing a penny off at 271p after
heavy turnover of 8.1m. Dealers said the initial strength followed reports
that the government had decided to drop legislation from the Queen's speech
planned for the autumn, which would introduce competition in the domestic
gas market in the UK.
Nomura was one broking house seeing the reports as possible good news for
British Gas. 'At a minimum it gives Gas's management more time to prepare
for a competitive market and with a general election looming in 1996-7 it
may be that competition will be postponed until the next century,' said Mr
Steve Turner of Nomura.
Television and leisure company Granada Group added 5 to 507p, after a modest
profits upgrade from Hoare Govett, its broker which is believed to have
increased its current year profits forecast by Pounds 6m to Pounds 250m.
The prospect of Thorn EMI demerging several of its businesses, together with
the hopes of a bullish trading statement at the group's annual meeting next
week, boosted the shares another 13 to 1039p.
Switching in the banks sector was not confined to RBOS and NatWest. There
was heavy trading in TSB where a block of 3m shares was sold into the market
at 195p.
The stock overhang in General Accident, which depressed it from mid-week
onwards, was said to have been partly cleared yesterday with the remainder
expected to be disposed of early on Monday. It closed 8 lower at 558p.
Turnover in Berkeley Group, the housebuilder hit 5.1m shares, with a block
of 2.4m traded at 390p and another of 2.2m at 393p.
Cable &amp; Wireless jumped 6 to 405p on good turnover of 4.6m, helped by buy
recommendations from Kleinwort Benson and NatWest Securities.
Engineering company TI hardend 4 to 358p, after James Capel reiterated its
buy recommendation. It drew attention to the impressive underlying growth at
the company. Reports that Smiths Industries had lost a lucrative contract
with Boeing left the shares trailing 6 to 435p.
Eurodollar, a vehicle distribution company issued at 220p, ended its first
day of trading at a 2p premium at 222p.
