<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUL 94 / International Company News: Saatchis stop Dreyfus buying
Adidas shares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM LEWIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Saatchi brothers, Maurice and Charles, have obtained a court order
preventing Mr Robert Louis-Dreyfus, a director of the advertising group they
founded, from buying shares in sports-wear producer Adidas.
Mr Louis Dreyfus moved from Saatchi &amp; Saatchi last year to become chief
executive of Adidas but stayed on as a non-executive director of the
advertising group.
Backed by a Pounds 260m (Dollars 395m) consortium that reportedly included
the two Saatchi brothers as well as Credit Lyonnais and Assurances Generales
de France (AGF), the insurance group, Dreyfus himself took a large stake in
the company.
In London's High Court this week the Saatchis and Hatzone, an investment
company half owned by Maurice Saatchi, won an undertaking from Mr
Louis-Dreyfus and Mr Christian Tourres that they would not buy Adidas shares
from seven companies.
The row over the shares is the latest to hit the Saatchi boardroom. Earlier
this year Mr Maurice Saatchi and Mr Charles Scott, both executive directors,
had a embarassing falling out in public over group strategy.
In April Adidas reported 1993 profits of DM9m against a loss of DM149m in
1992.
</TEXT>
